page.text: Mr. Curt P. Tappendorf, P.E., Senior Civil Engineer
Briarwood Mall, Addition of Two Restaurant Pads
At your request, Hubbell, Roth & Clark, Inc. prepared a traffic impact study for the two proposed
restaurant pads on the east side of Macy’s at Briarwood Mall in the City of Ann Arbor, Michigan. Based
on the site plan provided and shown in Figure 1, both will have outside seating in addition to the interior
dining area. The proposed restaurant pads are on the north side of the mall.
To meet the requirements of the City of Ann Arbor, HRC completed the following tasks:

 Requested and received signal timing plans from the City of Ann Arbor.
 Provided a description of the adjacent roadway system.
 Completed Midday and PM peak hour turning movement counts at the following intersections:
 Estimated the trips generated by the proposed land use using the techniques in the Institute of
 Distributed and assigned the site generated trips to the adjacent roadway system.
 Conducted a Mid-Day and PM peak hour capacity analyses using Synchro 8 software on the adjacent
roadway network using the techniques outlined in the Transportation Research Board 2010 Highway
 Prepared a report with our findings and recommendations.
Briarwood Mall is located at the southern edge of the City of Ann Arbor. It is located just north of I-94
and has access from State Street on the east and Eisenhower Parkway on the north. The mall is accessed
by a 4-lane ring road with three driveways to Eisenhower Parkway and three driveways to State Street. A
location map of Briarwood Mall is shown in Figure 2.
Eisenhower Parkway is a four-lane boulevard with a posted speed limit of 40 mph and 24-hour traffic
volumes of approximately 17,000 vehicles per day (vph). State Street is also a four-lane boulevard with a
posted speed of 35 mph and 24-hour traffic volumes of approximately 38,000 vpd. Both roads are under
the jurisdiction of the City of Ann Arbor.
Based on discussions with Pat Cawley, Senior Project Manager for the City of Ann Arbor, turning
movement counts were collections at the following intersections around the mall:
 Eisenhower Parkway and Main Street - Signalized
 Main Street and Briarwood Circle - Unsignalized, All-way Stop
 Eisenhower Parkway and Plaza Road - Unsignalized, Two-way Stop
 State Street and Briarwood Circle Drive - Signalized
 State Street and Hilton Boulevard - Unsignalized, Two-way Stop
The turning movement counts were collected on Tuesday, July 23, 2013 and Wednesday, July 24, 2013
Since the traffic counts were collected during July when school is out of session, seasonal factors were
researched to determine if the counts should be increased. According to the Southeast Michigan Council
of Governments (SEMCOG), the seasonal factor for a Wednesday in July based on 2012 traffic volumes
is 0.972. Applying this factor would result in decreasing the traffic volumes. In order to be on the
conservative side, the seasonal factor was not applied to the turning movement counts collected by HRC.
Counts were taken during the Mid-Day peak between 11:00 AM and 1:00 PM. The peak hour was 12:00

page.text: One of the most critical elements of a traffic impact study is estimating the amount of traffic to be
generated by a proposed development. This is usually done by using trip generation rates or equations to
provide an estimate of all future trips generated by a proposed development.
Rates are commonly expressed in trips per unit of development. For example, trips per dwelling unit are
commonly used for residential developments, while trips per 1,000 square feet of gross floor area are used
for offices and retail. Equations provide a direct estimate of trips based upon development units being
Trips are defined as a single or one directional movement with either the origin or destination of the trip
inside the study site. Thus, a car entering and leaving a site would be recorded as generating two trips.
Trip generation estimates are often the most critical factors in assessing impacts and needs of a proposed
There are several sources for trip generation rates and equations, which are based on data collected from
locations in the United States and Canada. These are compilations of data that have been gathered over
many years for various land uses. National data sources are starting points in estimating the amount of
traffic that may be generated by a specific building or land use. Whenever possible, the National rates
should be adjusted to reflect local or forecasted conditions. These National sources are not intended to be
used without question, deviation or sound judgment. They often reflect what are supposed to be the
average or typical conditions. Data collected from local sites may be more representative than National
averages of other developments within the area.
The most widely used source of national trip generation data is the Trip Generation Manual, published by
the Institute of Transportation Engineers (ITE). The information in this report is almost solely derived
from suburban and urban sites. Data included in trip generation was obtained from actual driveway
counts of vehicular traffic entering and exiting the site. The eighth edition contains more than 4,800 data
sets from individual trip generation studies. The report also includes discussions on the application and
use of trip generation rates and equations; descriptions of the characteristics of each land use;
maximum/minimum average rates for weekdays, weekends and peak hours of the generator and adjacent
street traffic; and additional statistical data regarding data variability.
HRC prepared trip generation estimates for the proposed restaurants using ITE Land Use Code 932, High-
Turnover Sit Down Restaurant, as shown in Attachment B. The trip generation could have been based on
ITE Land Use Code 931, Quality Restaurant, but that average rates for Land Use 932 are higher so the
trip generation results would be larger and reflect a worst case scenario. The following table shows the
number of trips expected during an average weekday Mid-Day peak hour and the PM peak hour of the

page.text: Mid-Day trip generation rates are not normally provided by the ITE Trip Generation Manual but this
Land use Code does provide an hourly variation by average weekday, Saturday and Sunday on page 1884
(see Attachment B). We utilized the same Mid-Day hour as determined by the turning movement counts,
12 noon to 1 PM, and applied the percent of entering and exiting vehicles for that hour.
The adjacent Briarwood Mall requires that we examine the impact of an internal capture rate on the total
new trips to be generated by the two restaurants. To be conservative, only the percentage of the total
development’s internal capture was used for the analysis. The worksheets for the Mid-Day and PM peak
internal capture rate are also provided in Attachment B. The worksheet showed that during the Mid-Day
peak hour, 3% of the trips would come from existing traffic at the mall and during the PM peak hour, the
internal capture rate is 2%. The reductions due to the internal capture rate are also shown in Table 3.
Traffic expected to be generated by a project must be distributed and assigned to the roadway system so
that the impacts of the proposed project on roadway links and intersections within the study area can be
analyzed. After an estimate of the total traffic into and out of the site has been made, that traffic must be
distributed and assigned to the roadway system. The trip distribution step produces estimates of trip
origins and destinations. The assignment step produces estimates of the amount of site traffic that will
use certain access routes between their origin and destination.
HRC distributed future traffic based on the existing turning movement counts on Eisenhower Pkwy and
on State Street. Figures 3 and 4 show the existing, site generated and future traffic volumes in the study
area for the Mid-Day and PM peaks, respectively.
HRC conducted a capacity analysis of the five intersections using Synchro 8. The intersections were
analyzed following the procedures for both signalized and un-signalized intersections as outlined in the
At an un-signalized intersection with stop control on the minor approach (Two Way Stop Controlled
intersections), LOS “F” occurs when there are not enough gaps of suitable size to allow a minor-street
demand to safely cross through traffic on the major street. This is typically evident from extremely long
control delays experienced by minor street traffic and by queuing on the minor approaches. LOS “F” may
also appear in the form of drivers on the minor street selecting smaller than usual gaps. In such cases,
safety may be a problem, and some disruption to the major traffic stream may result. Note that LOS “F”
may not always result in long queues but in adjustments to normal gap acceptance behavior, for example
a left-turning vehicle using a shorter than normal gap in traffic to complete the left-turn.
At Two Way Stop Controlled intersections, the critical movement, often the minor-street left-turn, may
control the overall performance of the intersection. The lower threshold for LOS “F” is set at 50 seconds
of delay per vehicle as shown in Table 4. In some cases, the delay equations will predict delays greater
than 50 seconds for minor-street movements under very low-volume conditions on the minor street (less
than 25 vehicles per hour). A LOS “F” threshold is reached with a movement capacity of approximately

page.text: At All Way Stop controlled intersections, every vehicle is required to stop at the intersection before
proceeding. The decision to proceed through the intersection is a function of traffic conditions on the
other approaches. If no other vehicles are present, the vehicle will proceed through the intersection as fast
as they can safely accelerate into and travel through. The LOS thresholds for control delay at All Way
Stop controlled intersections is the same as shown in Table 4.
At signalized intersections, the manual defines level of service in terms of control delay. Delay may be
measured in the field, or it may be estimated. Delay is a complex measure, and is dependent on a number
of variables, including the quality of progression, the cycle length, the green ratio, and the volume to
capacity ratio for the lane group or approach in question. Table 5 indicates the control delay criteria used
for determining level of service (LOS) for signalized intersections.

text.b: Table 5: Level of Service Criteria for Signalized Intersections

page.text: Level of Service A describes operations with very low control delay up to 10.0 sec per vehicle. This
occurs when progression is exceptionally favorable and most vehicles arrive during the green phase.
Most vehicles do not stop at all. Short cycle lengths may also contribute to low delay.
Level of Service B describes operations with control delay in the range of 10.1 to 20.0 sec per vehicle.
This generally occurs with good progression and/or short cycle lengths. More vehicles stop than for
Level of Service A, causing higher levels of average delay.
Level of Service C describes operations with control delay in the range of 20.1 to 35.0 sec per vehicle.
These higher delays may result from fair progression and/or longer cycle lengths. Individual cycle
failures may begin to appear in this level. The number of vehicles stopping is significant at this level,
although many still pass through the intersection without stopping.
Level of Service D describes operations with control delay in the range of 35.1 to 55.0 sec per vehicle. At
level D, the influence of congestion becomes more noticeable. Longer delays may result from some
combination of unfavorable progression, long cycle lengths, or high volume to capacity ratios. Many
vehicles stop, and the proportion of vehicles not stopping declines. Individual cycle failures are
Level of Service E describes operations with control delay in the range of 55.1 to 80.0 sec per vehicle.
This is considered to be above the limit of acceptable delay for an urban roadway in the study area. These
high delay values generally indicate poor progression, long cycle lengths, and high volume to capacity
ratios. Individual cycle failures are frequent occurrences.
Level of Service F describes operations with control delay in excess of 80.1 sec per vehicle. This is
considered to be unacceptable to most drivers. This condition often occurs with over saturation, i.e.,
when arrival flow rates exceed the capacity of the intersection. It may also occur at high volume to
capacity ratios below 1.00 with many individual cycle failures. Poor progression and long cycle lengths
may also be major contributing causes to such delay levels.
Results of capacity analysis of existing and future traffic volumes during the Mid-Day and PM peak hours
are provided in Tables 6 through 8. The Synchro reports are provided in Attachment C. Table 6 provides
the comparison of level of service for the two signalized intersections. Since Eisenhower Parkway is a
boulevard, the Synchro model treats the intersection as two separate intersections. The signal timings
permits were provided by the City of Ann Arbor. The City noted that the intersections of
Eisenhower/Main and State/Briarwood Circle Dr. are under SCOOT control. SCOOT is a fully adaptive
